Magnetic resonance imaging of lesions of the posterior fossa and upper cervical cord in childhood. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) promises to be an effective, noninvasive means of visualizing intracranial pathology. It should be especially useful in the evaluation of posterior fossa and cervical spinal cord disease of childhood computed tomographic (CT) evaluation is frequently suboptimal in this region. MRI results are reported for 46 consecutively seen children with posterior fossa and/or cervical spinal cord disease (28 had brain malignancies